{{no footnotes|date=November 2011}}{{Primarysources|article|date=November 2011}}
'''Emotional Selection''' is a [[psychological]] theory of [[dream|dreaming]] introduced in 2008 by Richard Coutts and refined in 2010.

Emotional selection describes a process that executes a set of [[Dream|dreams]] during [[non-REM sleep]] with content that is tentatively [[accommodation (psychology)|accommodated]] by [[Schema (psychology)|mental schemas]]. Because [[Schema (psychology)|schemas]] coexist as a [[wikt:network|network]], [[accommodation (psychology)|accommodations]] can introduce accidental, maladaptive conflicts and therefore are ideally tested prior to full integration. Consequently, during subsequent [[REM sleep]] a second set of [[Dream|dreams]] is executed in the form of [[scenario testing|test scenarios]]. If [[Schema (psychology)|schema]] [[accommodation (psychology)|accommodations]] performed during prior [[non-REM]] [[Dream|dreams]] alleviate anxiety, frustration, sadness, or in other ways appear [[emotions|emotionally]] adaptive during [[Rapid eye movement sleep|REM]] dream tests, they would be [[selection|selected]] for retention. Those [[accommodation (psychology)|accommodations]] that compare negatively to existing, unchanged [[Schema (psychology)|schemas]] would be abandoned or further modified and tested. 

[[Jean Piaget]] described [[Schema (psychology)|schemas]] as being riddled with conflict, which is why Coutts asserts that they are modified and tested with dreams during sleep. From his paper, "People strive for independence, yet find solace in the company of others; they place a high priority on our personal safety, yet quickly jeopardize it to help those in need; they are sexually attracted to many people, yet seek loving, [[monogamous]] relationships. [[Schema (psychology)|Schemas]] help strike the balances necessary for navigating the complex, often contradictory landscape that comprises life."{{cite quote}}

The [[Schema (psychology)|schemas]] targeted by emotional selection are those essential for meeting [[Maslow's hierarchy of needs|human needs]]. Consequently, emotional selection theory agrees with [[evolution|evolutionary]] forces by describing a role for [[Dream|dreams]] as adaptively enhancing [[Schema (psychology)|mental schemas]].

The theory of dreams selecting adaptive mental schemas can be considered 
a special case of the survival value of emotional communication in 
general. The german philosopher [[Ferdinand Fellmann]] proposed in 2009 
emotional selection  as a third form of evolutionary selection besides 
natural and sexual selection. Loving, monogamous pair-bonding  seems to 
be the favoured field where sexual selection is being transformed in 
emotional selection specific for human courtship and mating.

